The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 Shooting an eastern Western

 Screen On amp; Off

 With a master?s degree from the American 

 Film Institute, TASSADUQ HUSSAIN has given Omkara an 

 international look. He takes Pratim D. Gupta on a visual 

 tour

 Ajay Devgan and 

 Kareena Kapoor in Omkara 

 What have you shot before Omkara happened?

 I am from Kashmir and I initially 

 started out doing documentaries there. Then I did my Masters 

 in cinematography from the American Film Institute. After 

 that I started gaffing and assisting cinematographers for 

 music videos and short films. I mostly did independent films 

 including a Vietnamese film, a Korean movie and even small-budget 

 Hollywood films likes Dahmer. I got to work on a 

 Black Eyed Peas video and a Toyota commercial. Omkara 

 is my first feature film.

 How did you meet director Vishal Bhardwaj?

 I was here in Mumbai. I had seen 

 Maqbool and really liked it. Then I came to know 

 that he was adapting Othello and I just sent him 

 my (show) reel. He called me down from Kashmir and we met. 

 Our thoughts were very similar and we hit it off really 

 well.And we started working.

 What was the initial visual design for the film?

 I think the first image we came 

 up with was a lot of people as part of a large landscape. 

 From there on, we started developing ideas as per the need 

 of the script. The landscape was very important and became 

 a character of the movie. So we were very specific about 

 the kind of terrain we wanted to shoot in. We travelled 

 for one-and-a-half months through UP, from Allahabad to 

 Jhansi. Although later we shot here in Maharashtra, we kept 

 the northern UP texture in the landscape as the story was 

 faithful to the place.

 Everyone is calling it a Sergio Leone look. Was it intentional?

 (From top) Viveik 

 Oberoi, Konkona Sen Sharma, Naseeruddin Shah, Bipasha 

 Basu and Saif Ali Khan in moments from Omkara

 Vishal and I did talk about The 

 Good, the Bad and the Ugly as a possible inspiration 

 because even while writing the script, he was making an 

 eastern Western. I had watched The Good? when I was 

 really small and did not want to watch it again before shooting 

 Omkara. Because I felt the landscape and the sets 

 created on it had a strong character and feel of their own.

 Omkara?s village in the 

 film is a designed space in an open space. So I found it 

 as an alternative reality, which had elements of reality 

 yet had this magical quality about it. Only the opening 

 of the film has a sepia feel to it that pulls you towards 

 a warmer visual language. The rest of the colour palette 

 is very varied and dictated by moments. Overall, I feel, 

 the look is very original.

 It?s the first time you are shooting the biggest of Bollywood 

 stars. Anything special you found in them?

 All of the stars are very professional 

 and they take light really well. Changing lenses on Saif 

 did wonderful things to him and I could enter those emotional 

 spaces in him. When we used a wide lens, say 25, he looked 

 more like Iago, the sinister character he plays. And when 

 we used a longer lens, the image had more empathy for him 

 and you could actually go into his head. For his last shot 

 in the film I used a small eye light because there was a 

 lot of ambivalence, lot of speculation. So you as an audience 

 are not sure whether you know him as a person or you don?t.

 Can Omkara turn out to be a Saif Ali Khan film?

 People who have seen the film 

 have reacted in two ways. Some do feel it is Iago?s film 

 because he does manipulate things around and is largely 

 responsible for what is happening. Others, of course, find 

 it an Omkara film. But what Vishal has done and done it 

 well is make Omkara or Othello a lot less gullible than 

 he was in the original play.

 Everyone?s also talking about the way you have shot Kareena?

 We have used lighting in the film 

 to complement the person or the emotion. There are lots 

 of stars like Kareena and Bipasha who are performing on 

 a platform like this for the first time. So, many a time 

 I would ask Kareena not to come on the sets all made-up. 

 Without the make-up, I could feel her a lot more as an actor. 

 I have largely shot as I have been dictated by the given 

 moments in the movie.

 How would you rate the shooting experience in India vis-?-vis 

 shooting abroad?

 I was fortunate to be part of 

 a very organised set-up, which was as good as shooting anywhere 

 in the world. There was, of course, a whole lot of chaos 

 but that is part of the aesthetics and integral to Bombay 

 cinema. Of course, certain things are better here and certain 

 things better there. Both the set-ups have different strengths. 

 I did find the technicians, lightmen and production designers 

 really good and professional.

 Now that the film is ready for release, do you feel Vishal 

 has outdone himself after Maqbool?

 Maqbool and Omkara belong 

 to different spaces. Vishal?s definitely grown as a film-maker 

 but I wouldn?t say he?s outdone himself. Omkara is 

 a good piece of work, an entertaining movie with a lot of 

 subtle details that the audiences will enjoy. Vishal has 

 this wonderful imaginative power where he is able to create 

 original spaces that are not completely drawn from life 

 and exist only in his head.

 What would you be shooting after this?

 I don?t know. I have been getting 

 quite a few offers here but I would have to really want 

 to do something if I have to give six to eight months at 

 a stretch. By the end of July I am going back to Los Angeles 

 and meeting up with my friends. I am totally out of touch 

 with them and maybe some interesting work will come up for 

 me.




